segments.text: The library was my salvation for many reasons, and I'll get back to that later on.
But the first year I worked wherever I could.
I'd say I worked in horticulture.
I'd sometimes babysit for professors.
I was one of the early babysitters.
I can even remember the people I babysat for.
Some of them have just recently passed on.
Who?
Draper from poetry.
Do you remember him?
I call him Red, I believe.
He was red-headed.
They had a mean little boy.
Did they live on campus?
They lived, I think, in College Hills, I guess.
Everybody lived pretty close then and there.
I did weekend work for Professor Darnell in Daring.
I remember he worked me one whole afternoon where he was trimming his pecan.
I just had a pickup job.
But in the second semester of my freshman year, I got a pretty steady employment at the poultry farm, which was located...
Well, this side of the research park at that time.
Oh, west of the tracks.
Yeah, west on the campus.
And of course, nobody had cars.
I mean, there were no buses.
And you didn't have a bike.
No, no bike.
So you walked over.
We walked a lot.
But as I said, I preferred to, as I said, do my studying in short bursts.
And if I had an hour between classes, I always reworked my class notes.
and studied ahead, and I felt I was more efficient studying in bursts.
And as I said, that three or four hours in forced CQ was just awfully hard sometimes to stay awake at, because you couldn't talk to your roommate.
They'd catch you talking to your roommate, and you were in trouble.
You had to study.
And I think it probably was a good thing for many students, because they didn't horse around.
And you had to be accountable for who you were at the time.
on your schedule.
You had it posted on your doors so the upperclassmen would know where you were and so forth.
And if you were not accounted for, you'd probably hear about it.
But I stole time to some of my work situations, and then I discovered the library, and particularly between classes, I usually came to the library.
Did you have a special place in the library that was your... Yeah, I guess they refurnished all of that.
It was up in that big second floor reference room.
A nice place to study.
A cushion.
But that was pretty much the routine.
How did you learn all of the...
lingo, the... Well, it was beat into you.
But I was, to this day, I'm that way.
If I take a trip or something, I read everything I can about it.
And I say this, I'm still looking for it.
If you don't have this YMCA book, you need to find it.
Because it's only a pamphlet, but it was very specific about, you know, it had all the yells in it.
I memorized all those.
I memorized the words to the songs before I heard the tunes.
And we had lots of y'all practices where you learned these things.
And like I say, this thing where how you respond to, you never say no.
Sir, not having been informed for the highest degree of accuracy, I hesitate to articulate.
That type of thing.
And you're just learning.
The other thing you had to learn as a freshman on board, you had to know where every building was and when it was built.
And it had a good purpose to this day.
Frank, Frank, question about buildings that didn't exist.
As I said, learning the buildings made you
helpful to any visitor on the campus.
You had no trouble directing to any particular building on the campus.
Not only did we have to know the correct name, we had to know when it was built.
And in that first fall, how did you communicate with family back home?
Letters, just strictly letters.
About how often?
Well, this was the other thing.
This is why I say don't plan on going home.
That's the worst thing you could do.
Just stay the first semester and go home Christmas.
I guess, I don't know, I guess I did go home on Thanksgiving, I don't know.
I wrote a lot of letters to my mother, probably about weekly.
And did they write to you?
Oh yes.
Did you get any kush?
by mail?
No, I don't think so.
Some of the other guys did.
Did you all use that word then?
Yeah, of course, for dessert.
I never had a sweet tooth.
My mother knew that.
I never had much on dessert or sweet things.
She may have sent me some.
I can't remember, but I know it was always an occasion if somebody else got some because they'd either have to share it with you or else, but that was always an interesting day.
A mail call was
You really looked forward to mail.
You had, don't guess at that time I even had any female contacts.
Male call.
I didn't tell them about mail call.
There was not mail call.
You had a box.
There was a sub box down here.
What was the name of the old Casey's on the corner by the dorm?
They'd had part of that at the post office.
I don't recall.
Those were the charge boxes.
When I first came, you couldn't.
They were all full.
I had to go to Northgate to get my mail.
But mail from home was just like in the military.
You really, I mean, you went by every day even though you didn't get one or two things of leave.
But I guess, as I said, I didn't have a girlfriend at that time.
And a lot of the other guys didn't.
A lot of the problems, I think, that some of the people had in adjusting was many of them had high school sweethearts.
And it was a sore process of breaking up that they were all needed, you know, because of the distance involved.
Describe your impression of your first Yale practice and first football game.
Well, I have to even go back to this.
I guess that was enough to have scared me off of the place before I got down here.
As I recall, the school didn't start until late September.
It lasted until late January, all semester.
But I think even before I came down here, maybe it was the first week or so, I can't remember.
We played Texas Tech at the Alamo Stadium in San Antonio.
And I went there, and I don't know how they found out I was a freshman.
I can't remember.
Maybe it was after he started.
Anyway, I got a lot of abuse there from upperclassmen.
And, you know, hump it and yell at me.
It was all just.
a big blur to me.
I didn't even know all the L's.
I mean, I said I'd studied them before, but it was different.
But anyway, that was my first, I guess, real contact with some of the upperclassmen and their behavior.
But that was pretty much it.
I kept promising myself, just hang on for a year.
I mean, just whatever it does to hang on, just, I mean,
The drop-off rate was horrific.
I mean, I went anywhere from a third to a half when I dropped out.
As you look back on that, about how many of the students left because of grades and how many left because of some other reason?
Do you have any guess?
I don't know.
People rationalize.
It was hard to admit that you were leaving because of the core activities.
They would...
I guess most of them pleaded academic problems, but it was pretty tough here for most, a lot of students.
I mean, the professors were, you know, A's and B's weren't very, very available.
The professors weren't pretty, a lot of professors, I'd say, had the core spirit.
I mean, they expected discipline in there, too, and I guess some of them were former Aggies.
Did you have any faculty, any instructors that first year that you now realize were quite important to you?
Oh, yes, very definitely.
I had one that,
It was very important, Fred Bryson and Dr. Abrams.
Please, please.
I worked with those two guys.
I mean, I just took one course, I think.
Dr. Abrams was a wonderful professor.
And Fred Bryson, I guess I took a course from him later on.
What made them special?
The fact that you were a human being, and you could talk to them.
Did you know Fred Bryson?
He was a great jokester, as you know.
He somewhat embarrassed me years later.
I'm going aside here.
Oh, that's all right.
Years later.
He never forgot a student.
I mean, years later, he'd know you in a crowd.
And that shows that he did care.
But anyway, I remember it was four or five years after I graduated.
And I was a county agent.
And they often brought us here for what they call short courses to update you and various things.
And he was doing this.
skill things with budding and grafting.
You know what a whip graft is?
You know where you split the two signs and you put them together and you have to make them fit very well and then you put wax on them and wrap them and all that.
Anyway, the fit is very important.
And this was five years or so after I was out from that school.
And he suggested you hold it up to the light.
I mean, this way, see if you see any light coming through there because if you did, you didn't have a good fit.
And he said, of course, when Faustia was here, you could see the dome of the Academia.
I was embarrassed, but pleased that he still remembered me.
But he was very, those two were very important, even though I had no intention at that time of going into agriculture.
Let me see if there were any other professors that are particularly, I had Darbor in animal science,
I said I didn't have too much contact with my advisor, I would say that Adriens and Bryson kind of became my informal advisors, and they were very supportive.
And then when I started working for the poultry farm, the head of the department at that time, I should remember his name, kindly old gentleman, I'm sorry it escapes me now, but he was
understood my situation, and I had, you know, taken care of poultry before in my life, and he was, gave me this job over at the poultry farm, which I enjoyed and worked over there.
Do you remember your first silver taps?
Yes, I guess so.
I mean, what did it?
Let me say that the first year was just a,
I don't know how to say it.
Just almost a dream, or a nightmare, I guess.
You did, I was, my objective was academics.
I mean, I was determined to do my academics in spite of the Corps type of thing.
And there's some people, I guess, who tried to get out of the Corps.
I guess the rule at that time was that
You could not, you had to be in the Corps the first two years unless you had previous military service or had a physical disability.
And some of them, I know I forgot, they were some people who managed to get out of the Corps.
They had another bad term in that time.
It was, and some of the locals were the children of the faculty members and other people lived there.
Call them the day duckers, heard that term.
They had their own unit.
They attended ROTC classes, but they hadn't
They were very much supposedly looked down upon by the elite corps members.
I guess, unless you want to...
I didn't respond to your other question.
What was it now?
I don't remember right now.
You went to football games.
You got involved in everything.
You were required to go to football games.
Locally, you marched in, like they do now.
And you were required to go to corps games
At that time, in the Southwest Conference, the schedules were firm for year after year after year.
We played SMU, TCU, University of Texas, Rice.
When the games were in Houston or Dallas or Waco or Austin, we always went and we hitchhiked.
It was always hitchhiking.
Do you remember any good experiences from a court trip game?
Good meaning memorable, plus or minus?
Well, again, it was sort of a...
I'm trying to think of the word.
See when you hitchhiked, you left like Friday after classes and no telling when you'd get there.
Sometimes you'd get a direct route, sometimes you'd have to, usually you'd have to get two or three routes.
It often was very late before you got there, sometimes.
And then you always had, before the game, the games were usually in the afternoon, you had the Corps parade in the morning.
And then you went straight to the football game.
And, of course, you stood the whole time there.
Do you remember any negative experiences involving local people on a court trip?
No, not really.
I haven't run into any.
No, not at all.
And hitchhiking was a very positive thing.
A&M had a reputation.
There was a procedure.
You couldn't upstream.
That has a big meaning.
And there was a designated location in every town, including here.
And you just got in line.
And any citizen, I don't care who they were, with your uniform, invariably almost picked you up.
And we imagine how many.
There were several hundred that went to a court trip on a weekend.
We all got there.
We couldn't afford to go any other way.
Maybe the band, I guess the band and the team traveled by bus.
But the rest of us all had to get there on our own.
Did you hitchhike to home?
Oh, yes, always.
And my mother hated it.
She thought the worst could possibly happen.
I did have some interesting experiences.
But no, it was a part of my economy.
I could actually most times get there faster hitchhiking than I could.
What route did you normally take hitchhiking?
Well, since I said I'd live close to Randolph Field, I'd get my parents there.
very reluctantly on my mother's part just to dump me at the close to where the turnoff is to Randolph Field on what we call the Austin Highway.
It's now 35, 81 I guess.
And usually you'd catch a ride pretty fast.
Sometimes you'd have to go through Austin.
And then you'd have to get yourself across town.
And sometimes you'd get a direct.
But sometimes, more times than not, you'd get a direct.
And there were some few students and veterans who were going home on weekends.
And I'd go out there on a Sunday morning, Sunday, no, I guess usually on a Sunday afternoon if I went home.
As I said, I didn't go home very much.
That was more later that I started going home a little more.
But I preferred to hitchhike because it was more efficient and saved that little bit of money.
You said some interesting experiences hitchhiking.

Oh, one time I got with, coming out of San Antonio, I got with a guy who was, I sort of hoped he'd let me drive, he was drinking while he was taking slugs from the, he had a girlfriend over there, and I somehow got out of that, he was going to take me further, but I used some excuse, I had to get off or something, but most of the time it was favorable, you met people who were interesting, and
But as I said, it was the way to go.
You never had anybody attempt anything?
No.
I have not yet had a single negative experience.
This was the only thing the guy was drinking, like that.
I mean, he was just a drunk.
That's all I've said.
And I discovered that pretty soon.
And as I said, I got out of it.
But I think all the other occasions were positive.
Later on, I guess as I became a junior or senior,
I made connections with another student from the general area who had a car and went home often and I'd share gas and ink cost or something with him.
But hitchhiking was the way to go.
That first semester, your grades, how'd you do?
I did pretty well.
I think I got, as I said, I exempted
I don't know.
I haven't looked at my transcript.
I made mostly A's and B's, maybe one or two C's.
Did you think about ever going home, quitting, dropping out?
All the time.
But I couldn't.
I mean, that was my darn decision.
You know, if my parents had said, you must go to A&M, I'm sure I would have quit.
But, you know, they tried to talk me out of it.
I mean, they didn't want me not to go to college.
They said, why don't you go to junior college?
There was San Antonio Junior College.
Take you two years there, and then you still want to go on, you know.

you know still could stay on home on the farm and you know I was the only son and I guess in the back they had maybe hoped that I'd take over the operation but I didn't see too much future there but no I quitting was but I I finally just made the resolve I mean things got very bad many times it was not for the academics I enjoyed the academics but the core thing got pretty bad and I did you know think many times that you know I could understand why others quit but I kept resolving
Did you and your buddies ever attempt any pranks on upperclassmen when you were a freshman?
Some of my colleagues did.
I did everything to avoid trouble.
I mean, there was enough trouble coming your way without looking for it.
But there was a lot of that going on.
And as I said, I had to work.
Those that didn't have to work, I guess, had more time for those kind of things.
Do you remember...
even in your outfit or anywhere else, any good bull pranks that are worthy of?
Yeah, I remember two that were pretty good.
Every once in a while at administration, there'd be some hazing problem erupt in the public.
And so there'd be a sudden crackdown.
And the biggest fun, I guess, the students had was with the KKs.
You know the KKs?
Campus cops.
They were always pulling pranks on them more than anything else.
I remember, I don't know which year this was, but it was one of those cases where they were really cracking down on hazing.
The windows were usually open and anybody who walked through that area could tell when paddling was going on just by the sound.
effort to drive, as I said, the K.K.
's mad by tying a pillow on the bedstead or frame of a bed and paddling it.
And they'd come, you know, everybody, here they come, you know, type of thing.
And it was not unusual for where the steps and the windows were arranged on the dormitories, if a K.K.
came into the building, he'd have a dump of whole garbage can of water on him.
And, you know,
They'd disappear.
Everybody would disappear.
Nobody knew anything.
And there was this solidarity of not ratting was a big one when something like that happened.
Another, well, this wasn't a prank, but it was an indication of the esteem in which the students had for the KKs.
This is a true story.
We had one of the guys in the unit who was a real cowboy.
And apparently, he came from a fairly well-to-do family, and he could afford to keep a horse down here.
And he had a Cadillac, a brand new Cadillac with a trailer hitch and he pulled his horse around and everything.
And he came to class one day really upset that he had gotten a ticket, a parking ticket.
And what he had done, he had bought a new rope, and new ropes are pretty stiff.
So what he did in the parking lot, wherever he parked, he tied the one end to a tree and the other end to the car and pulled it tight to make it stretch overnight.
And the ticket didn't specify what it was for, so he, you know, he went, they called the arresting, the ticketing officer in.
He said, well, he assumed the car just didn't have any brakes.
He had to take it.
I don't know if that story was true, but it was sort of the, an indication of what the
what the students thought about the KKs at those days.
In your outfit, now listen, did your outfit have a nickname?
You asked me that.
Oh, I can't remember.
I can't remember.
In your outfit, did anybody ever do any unusual, play any unusual good bull tricks at mealtime on some software?
Oh, I can't remember.
I know one thing that occasionally happened in the
That's always the food fights.
I don't know what precipitated those, but people just started throwing food at each other, mostly biscuits and stuff like that.
Who had to clean up?
I don't know.
You fish didn't have to clean that up?
No, not such, but a lot of Aggies worked as waiters.
All the waiters were.
And a lot of the other work was done by students.
I mean, employment was given up.
All the waiters were students, which was a pretty good job because you'd only work about 40 minutes three times a day and you'd have to eat anyway.
But there were students used for janitorial purposes and all of that all over.
So it was sort of the policy of the university was to give opportunities.
I think that grew out of the Depression years with the project houses and all that.
As far as you knew, what were the best jobs for a student on campus?
What were they?
Well, as I implied earlier, I got very, very lucky the second year.
In the sophomore year, of course, I'd learned my way around.
But I still knew, and I didn't want, as I said, I didn't want to get into the hazing of freshmen as I had been hazed.
And I...
resolved to minimize my core activities to the extent possible.
I have to indicate one thing that happened that second year is that there was a huge increase in enrollment.
We had to triple up in the dormitory rooms which were big enough for two.
They actually put another cop, three deckers, in rooms and it was very unsatisfactory because you know when you're two in a room or two people together, if you don't want to
have conversation, you just don't participate, you just don't do anything, but if your two roommates do, you know.

It was not a very good arrangement, and I had to get out of that, I mean, and I started looking, the minute I came back on my second year of my sophomore year, I started looking for a job, and I stumbled into the Cushing Library, and I got a job.
And that was the happiest thing that ever happened to me, or the best thing that ever happened to me.
How did that come about?
I just was looking for a job.
Did you go over to the library and ask?
Yeah, I just walked up and asked.
Because I knew there were some students working there, and I had no idea.
I guess I probably learned that this was a good situation, but I wasn't too hopeful.
But I was hired right away and stayed here the next three years, working in the library.
Doing what?
Well, you started off at the very bottom.
In those days, students did not have access to the stacks.

On the second floor of the old library, Cushing Library, there was a big desk, and there were usually a senior, not a senior person, but a regular employee operating the desk with the help of, depending on the time of day, three or four student help.
And you could work during the day according to your schedule, or at night, or whatever.
And what the students would do, would look up the book they'd want, and you'd fill out a card with a reference, and you'd run down,
stacks to either run the elevator or usually go and put, get the book, check it out to them, and that's what you did.
That was the lowest.
But you could even there get breaks to study.
I mean, you didn't have any book breaks, you know, that type of thing.
And the, you worked your way up.
And I think by my second and third year, I got to, in the reading room, they had the reserve show.
And somebody had to operate the reserve books.
Mm-hmm.
And that was a wonderful job because usually in the evening or in the afternoons, I put most of my time in on weekends.
I worked every time I could on Saturdays and Sundays.
You'd have a flurry of activity at the beginning of a period, like 7 o'clock, and then 10 or 11, turning it in.
But in between, it was pretty slow.
Nobody there to bother you.
And you could really study, and that was the wonderful thing about it.
And I think the other thing that I really appreciated about working in the library, I learned how to use the library.
Who was the librarian in those days?
Tommy Mayo?
Was he still around?
Give me another name.
I had very little contact with him.
I don't know.
I do have one.
I do have a story about one of the incidences.
Please do.
There was a Dr. Potter, I believe was his name, in zoology, or zoology somewhere, and he produced tomes, I mean, big textbooks, and he did his research.
And the routine at the library was, this was when I was still working the stacks, was that about, I think the library closed at 10 or 11, whatever it was, and about 20 minutes before,
graduate students and faculty members had access to the stacks, and a lot of them did their research and they'd get off to a corner near the books that they wanted and do their research.
Well, it may have been Mayo, but I don't know.
It was the library head at the time.
It wasn't him.
It was somebody else.
But anyway, I didn't know of Dr. Potter's reputation, but anyway, I came through.
Our job was to
And I went through and did my, what were they, 11 or 12 stacks, you know, you went through the whole thing warning people.
Then you'd come back and shut the light, check to see where anybody was.
And I went back a second time, and he was gone, so I put the lights out.
They had to hold me put out manually and report it up to the supervisor that took care of it.
But I didn't know, Dr. Potter wanted to work a little longer.
And as soon as I left, he put the lights back on and kept working.
And about 2 or 3 a.m., he decided he was ready to quit.
He couldn't get out of the building.
And he called the head librarian to let him out.
And I was told that story the next day, and I thought, you know, I'm going to be fired, right?
And I mean, I think it was the head librarian.
I can't remember the name.
Anyway, he was very somber about it, you know.
And I said, you know...
I thought the least I'd get by with would be a lawsome job hanging after that.
Anyway, he chewed me out.
Then after that, he laughed.
He said, this had happened before, more than once.
They thought they wanted to just give him a key.
Anyway, that was an NRA.
But as I said, the wonderful thing was, particularly in my master's and doctorate program, I could use the library like nobody else because I knew where things were and how to use it and everything.
And the library must have been almost a sanctuary for the whole campus.
Oh, yeah, yeah.
But I think, again, students didn't use it so much as they should have.
I think, like the reserve thing was used because there were firm assignments made, you know, read this and so on, publish a book and so forth.
But students just going to the library to go to the library, I mean, that was sort of...
But they also did not misuse it.
No, no.
They didn't.
They misrespected it.
No mischief in the library.
No, no.
And the reading room was quiet.
You could hear a pin drop.
And occasionally, did a student slump over the table and go to sleep?
Oh, yeah.
And I guess that's where corporate.
You had to get some sleep somewhere.
And it was hard to stay.
I mean, as I said, particularly when they roused you up at night to do some foolish thing.
sleep was just the most precious commodity there was.
A lot of classes, students just could not stay awake.
To me, that was the worst aspect of the core life, was the fact that you just never had enough sleep.
Never had enough sleep, and you'd see people stretched out wherever they could.
Right, now we're about to finish this first tape.
Describe your feelings as you go home at the end of that freshman year.
Well, relief that I survived.
great relief that I survived, and a commitment to go back and try to do better next time.
And as I said, my feeling about the Corps was that although these things were done to me, I was resolved I would never be a party to them.
And I never, as I said, never once picked up the paddle against anybody.
I avoided it.
They'd happen, other than my colleagues did, but I didn't.
And I avoided it, somehow avoided it completely.
